			<h2 class="date-header">Monday, March 14, 2005</h2>
	
	<div class="entry" id="entry-3947875">
					<h3 class="entry-header">Best use of a tomato, bacon and egg</h3>
		
		<div class="entry-content">
			<div class="entry-body">
				<p><a href="http://seattlebonvivant.typepad.com/.shared/image.html?/photos/uncategorized/aa.JPG" onclick="window.open(this.href, '_blank', 'width=640,height=480,scrollbars=no,resizable=no,toolbar=no,directories=no,location=no,menubar=no,status=no,left=0,top=0'); return false"><img width="300" height="225" border="0" alt="Aa" title="Aa" src="http://seattlebonvivant.typepad.com/seattle_bon_vivant/images/aa.JPG" /></a>
</p>

<p>
Around these parts, Mr. C is quite notorious for his fabulous Sunday breakfasts. Yesterday, with wonderful bacon at hand, a couple gorgeous tomatoes and fresh market eggs he was taking requests from the kitchen.</p>

<p>So I begged for one of my favorite, albeit rarely eaten treats: A simple bacon, egg and tomato--on slightly toasted buttermilk bread-- sandwich. 

</p>

<p>If I tell you this was one of the best sandwiches I've ever had it will still be an understatement. It was just heavenly. The bacon was cooked to perfection and it had the most beautiful rosy hue. </p>

<p>The tomatoes heated through just enough and the egg, oh the egg! Cooked well with an intensely yellow and very&nbsp; runny yolk that painted the insides of the sandwich with a sunny, happy and flavorful disposition. 

</p>

<p>Funny thing is how while eating this beauty, uttering too many <em>mmmms</em> and watching Mr. C's big grin--a job well done indeed-- I kept thinking how great of an entry this would have been for Jeanne's <strong><a href="http://cooksister.typepad.com/cook_sister/">EoMEoTE </a></strong>#4. ;-) </p>
			</div>
			
			
			
		</div>
		<p class="entry-footer">
			<span class="post-footers">07:15 AM</span> <span class="separator">|</span> <a class="permalink" href="http://seattlebonvivant.typepad.com/seattle_bon_vivant/2005/03/best_use_of_a_t.html">Permalink</a>
							| <a href="http://seattlebonvivant.typepad.com/seattle_bon_vivant/2005/03/best_use_of_a_t.html#comments">Comments (1)</a>
			
			
		</p>
	</div>
			<h2 class="date-header">Friday, October 01, 2004</h2>
	
	<div class="entry" id="entry-2281706">
					<h3 class="entry-header">Breakfast: Michel Montignac Cassis Jam</h3>
		
		<div class="entry-content">
			<div class="entry-body">
				<p><a href="http://seattlebonvivant.typepad.com/photos/uncategorized/breakfast_2.JPG" onclick="window.open(this.href, '_blank', 'width=448,height=336,scrollbars=no,resizable=no,toolbar=no,directories=no,location=no,menubar=no,status=no,left=0,top=0'); return false"><img alt="Breakfast_2" title="Breakfast_2" src="http://seattlebonvivant.typepad.com/seattle_bon_vivant/images/breakfast_2.JPG" width="200" height="150" border="0"  /></a><BR><BR>While in Paris, I met with the fabulous Ms. N, a dear friend and partner in crime. We went to the Trade Show together, had lovely lunches, too many laugh out loud episodes, long conversations on everything and anything (especially on business, fragrance, makeup and food related) and did some shopping too. Of course! </p>

<p>Since she knew how much I loved good jams , before I left, she presented me with a jar of her favorite: <strong><strong><A href="http://www.montignac-intl.com/">Michel Montignac</A></strong> Cassis Jam</strong>. Now, Mr. Montignac is a healthy eating <strong><A href="http://www.montignac-intl.com/En/mm1en.html">guru</A></strong> known all over France and Europe for his <strong><em>Méthode Montignac</em></strong>. His first book, <strong>Eat Yourself Slim</strong>, has sold over 10 million copies worldwide (funny enough it is not available for sale in France, where his books are prohibited from distribution) so he preaches his healthy gospel through lectures and from his website instead.</p>

<p><strong><A href="http://www.montignac.co.uk/inthepress/dailystar.htm">Kylie Minogue</A></strong> is a reported fan and attributes her slim figure (she was having lunch with her friends next to Mr C and I last April at <strong>Café Le Flore</strong> and I can attest as to her very <em>ultra petite</em> frame) to his <em>dietetique nutritionnelle</em>. N told me his products, including the jams are sold at health food stores (and at <strong><A href="http://www.monoprix.fr/">Monoprix</A></strong> too). So my initial thought was "hmm...<em>health food</em> jam? This better be good! Ha! ;-D</p>

<p>I am happy to report it is indeed! Though Montignac's jam is nothing like my all time favorite jams such as those made by <strong>Christine Ferber</strong> or <strong>Fauchon</strong> --they have no sugar added, sweetened instead with concentrated fruit extracts-- it is lovely nonetheless. </p>

<p>The <strong>Cassis</strong> (Black Currant) has a beautiful color,  sheen, texture, consistency and spreads beautifully. It <em>is</em>, naturally, a <u>lot</u> less sweet than 95% of the jams in the market. But I guess anyone looking to watch their figure or reduce sugar intake or just do not like sicky sweet jams will appreciate this product. I had it with my morning tea (<strong>Maxim's De Paris Earl Grey</strong>) and toast yesterday and again today and it was just wonderful.</p>

<p>Although I'm not ready to eschew all other jams and switch to Montignac's méthode anytime soon, it is wonderful to know there are great quality sugar free jams such as these out there for those who do not want to give up  their morning jam but need or want to make adjustments to their sugar intake.</p>

<p><br />
<strong><A href="http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/search-handle-url/index=books&field-author=Michel%20Montignac/102-1397934-1782551">Michel Montignac on amazon.com</A></strong></p>
			</div>
			
			
			
		</div>
		<p class="entry-footer">
			<span class="post-footers">09:32 AM</span> <span class="separator">|</span> <a class="permalink" href="http://seattlebonvivant.typepad.com/seattle_bon_vivant/2004/10/breakfast.html">Permalink</a>
							| <a href="http://seattlebonvivant.typepad.com/seattle_bon_vivant/2004/10/breakfast.html#comments">Comments (2)</a>
			
			
		</p>
	</div>
			<h2 class="date-header">Tuesday, August 10, 2004</h2>
	
	<div class="entry" id="entry-1938722">
					<h3 class="entry-header">Washington Green Figs</h3>
		
		<div class="entry-content">
			<div class="entry-body">
				<p><a href="http://seattlebonvivant.typepad.com/seattle_bon_vivant/images/washington_green_fig_on_tree1.html" onclick="window.open('http://seattlebonvivant.typepad.com/seattle_bon_vivant/images/washington_green_fig_on_tree1.html','popup','width=448,height=336,scrollbars=no,resizable=no,toolbar=no,directories=no,location=no,menubar=no,status=no,left=0,top=0'); return false"><img alt="washington_green_fig_on_tree" src="http://seattlebonvivant.typepad.com/seattle_bon_vivant/images/washington_green_fig_on_tree-thumb.JPG" width="149" height="112" border="0" style="float: right; margin: 0px 0px 5px 5px;" /></a>Last week I posted about a lovely meal of chicken, sweet potatoes, tomato salad and <strong><A href="http://seattlebonvivant.typepad.com/seattle_bon_vivant/2004/08/grilled_figs.html">grilled fig kabobs</A></strong> we have had. The figs, came from a friendly West Seattle couple, who shared a bag of fresh figs from their garden with us, while we waited together at the Ferry Terminal on our way to Bainbridge Island. </p>

<p>We had exchanged phone numbers before boarding the ferry (in our cars). After gushing about my love for all things fig, they invited me to come over to their West Seattle home and see the <strong><A href="http://66.102.7.104/search?q=cache:mVD27I7tIG4J:www.campusprogram.com/reference/en/wikipedia/f/fi/fig.html+washington+figs&hl=en">Washington Green Fig</A></strong> tree for myself, collect some fruit and perhaps witness some of the local <strong><A href="http://www.csmonitor.com/2003/0710/p13s02-sten.html">starlings</A></strong>, who drunk on fermented figs, fly around the garden, crazed. </p>

<p>Today was a very warm, sunny and lovely afternoon in Seattle. So, after a very long work day that started too early this morning, I drove to Pigeon Point to visit with Laura and her fig tree. The tree's main crop is almost completely harvested by now but a new crop is coming out. Perhaps, aided by a Seattle <em>Indian Summer</em>, it can mature by late September/October for yet a second helping. Even so,  today the tree looked gorgeous. Full of ripe figs, past their prime figs, picked to death by the birds figs and young, just starting to grow <strong><A href="http://www.hort.purdue.edu/newcrop/morton/fig.html">figs</A></strong>. So wonderful to see an old <em>figuier</em> like this one, still producing delicious fruit. </p>

<p><a href="http://seattlebonvivant.typepad.com/seattle_bon_vivant/images/fig_rhubarb_jam1.html" onclick="window.open('http://seattlebonvivant.typepad.com/seattle_bon_vivant/images/fig_rhubarb_jam1.html','popup','width=336,height=448,scrollbars=no,resizable=no,toolbar=no,directories=no,location=no,menubar=no,status=no,left=0,top=0'); return false"><img alt="fig_rhubarb_jam" src="http://seattlebonvivant.typepad.com/seattle_bon_vivant/images/fig_rhubarb_jam-thumb.JPG" width="150" height="200" border="0" style="float: left; margin: 0px 5px 5px 0px;" /></a>How lucky I felt to be able to see the tree in person. To be invited to its home. To get a chance to touch its leaves and take pictures of its fruit.   </p>

<p>I got the full tour. The homeowner's personal and quite extensive art glass collection (including many pieces from the <strong><A href="http://www.glasseye.com/">Glass Eye Studio</A></strong>). Arts and crafts of all kinds, most made by her. I was even offered a spoonful of <strong>Fresh Fig Rhubarb Jam</strong> made by the owner (amazingly yummy) to try (from the last jar no less). She call it her Fantasy Jam and even shared the recipe with me . She also showed me more of her refrigerator's fruity bounty including a bag of frozen fig pulp (processed, skins and all, using a juicer). It was the color of guavas. Just beautiful.</p>

<p><a href="http://seattlebonvivant.typepad.com/seattle_bon_vivant/images/stepping_stones.html" onclick="window.open('http://seattlebonvivant.typepad.com/seattle_bon_vivant/images/stepping_stones.html','popup','width=448,height=336,scrollbars=no,resizable=no,toolbar=no,directories=no,location=no,menubar=no,status=no,left=0,top=0'); return false"><img alt="stepping_stones" src="http://seattlebonvivant.typepad.com/seattle_bon_vivant/images/stepping_stones-thumb.JPG" width="149" height="112" border="0" style="float: right; margin: 0px 0px 5px 5px;" /></a>What a garden! What a house! Full of little wonders everywhere. A koi pond,  flower pots hand made with pieces of pottery and old china. Carved and stones with faces and sayings.  Beautiful stepping stones. and other lovely handmade garden decorations. </p>

<p>After visiting with Buck, the labrador once again (such a sweet dog!) and chatting about figs, jam, art glass and the joys of all things homemade, I was sent home with a bag full of beautifully bright green and oh so ripe and delectable figs. I'm immensily thankful for the invite and so glad I made the trek uphill to West Seattle. Now its a matter of getting started with the jam. Will try to post about it in a few days.</p>
			</div>
			
			
			
		</div>
		<p class="entry-footer">
			<span class="post-footers">11:08 PM</span> <span class="separator">|</span> <a class="permalink" href="http://seattlebonvivant.typepad.com/seattle_bon_vivant/2004/08/west_seattle_wa.html">Permalink</a>
							| <a href="http://seattlebonvivant.typepad.com/seattle_bon_vivant/2004/08/west_seattle_wa.html#comments">Comments (0)</a>
			
			
		</p>
	</div>
			<h2 class="date-header">Friday, July 23, 2004</h2>
	
	<div class="entry" id="entry-1831025">
					<h3 class="entry-header">Summer in Seattle means Gelatiamo!</h3>
		
		<div class="entry-content">
			<div class="entry-body">
				<p><a href="http://seattlebonvivant.typepad.com/seattle_bon_vivant/images/rice_pistachio_chocolate_ice_creams_from_gelatiamo.html" onclick="window.open('http://seattlebonvivant.typepad.com/seattle_bon_vivant/images/rice_pistachio_chocolate_ice_creams_from_gelatiamo.html','popup','width=426,height=336,scrollbars=no,resizable=no,toolbar=no,directories=no,location=no,menubar=no,status=no,left=0,top=0'); return false"><img alt="rice_pistachio_chocolate_ice_creams_from_gelatiamo" src="http://seattlebonvivant.typepad.com/seattle_bon_vivant/images/rice_pistachio_chocolate_ice_creams_from_gelatiamo-thumb.JPG" width="275" height="216" border="0" style="float: left; margin: 0px 5px 5px 0px;" /></a>Ahh! Summer in Seattle. It is indeed dreamy. Gorgeous weather. Long sunny and warm days with beautiful blue skies. Driving down <strong>I-5</strong> is a joy, even in traffic, when you look at the end of the road and all you see is the big and beautiful ice cream cone that is <strong>Mount Rainier</strong>. Sitting there, staring you out, winking at you, teasing you from afar. An immense cone of Ice Cream.</p>

<p>Yesterday morning I was driving down I-5 towards <strong>Burien</strong>, distracted by the gorgeous day, admiring the weather and counting my blessings. In fact, the blessings of all Seattleites. I was once again reminded of <strong>how lucky we are to live in this beautiful city</strong>. G-d's country really. How Mount Rainier, on a clear, crisp and sunny day like today, seems as if it is at arm's length, just at the end of the road. Rainier,  with a clearly visible summit, even from afar, all covered in snow, seemed <em>so</em> close. So lovely I get a bit <em>verklempt</em> every time I see it, every time I think about it. Every time I spot the mountain. Every single time it plays peek-a-boo with me (how some can get used to this beauty, take for granted the amazing views of our fair city is beyond me). </p>

<p>After arriving in Burien, to do some work, shop Trader Joe's and <strong>Burien Farmers Market</strong>, I could not get the idea of the big ice cream cone out of my head. With temperatures reaching the mid 80's and barely a breeze in the air, the sun as hot as can be, I was already looking forward to heading back home, a chilled 68F (my ideal temp) and finding something cold to drink or eat (not to mention put away my market purchases, especially the week's worth of Greek yogurt I had purchased at Trader Joe's). Grilling was out of the question. Just too darn hot.</p>

<p>Then, an epiphany! <strong>Gelatiamo!</strong> I barely had time to park my car in the garage and put my market loot away when we were out the door and off to 3rd and Union, caddy corner with Benaroya Hall, across from the 98101 US Postal Office and Wild Ginger on the other side of the street. </p>

<p><a href="http://seattlebonvivant.typepad.com/seattle_bon_vivant/images/Gelatiamo2.html" onclick="window.open('http://seattlebonvivant.typepad.com/seattle_bon_vivant/images/Gelatiamo2.html','popup','width=448,height=336,scrollbars=no,resizable=no,toolbar=no,directories=no,location=no,menubar=no,status=no,left=0,top=0'); return false"><img alt="Gelatiamo2" src="http://seattlebonvivant.typepad.com/seattle_bon_vivant/images/Gelatiamo2-thumb.JPG" width="149" height="112" border="0" style="float: right; margin: 0px 0px 5px 5px;" /></a>Gelatiamo makes, right here in Seattle, the best Gelato and sorbetto this side of Rome and Paris. The selection is amazing. They also have beautiful pastries and cakes to order. Italian espressos, cappuccinos, and lattes. The servers are friendly and seem to really enjoy what they do. So, it was Rice, Pistachio, Chocolate and Strawberry for the three of us. Served in the traditional ice cold metal dishes. With a lovely crispy and light as a feather butter and sugar cookie. Bliss! </p>

<p><a href="http://seattlebonvivant.typepad.com/seattle_bon_vivant/images/Gelatiamo3.html" onclick="window.open('http://seattlebonvivant.typepad.com/seattle_bon_vivant/images/Gelatiamo3.html','popup','width=448,height=336,scrollbars=no,resizable=no,toolbar=no,directories=no,location=no,menubar=no,status=no,left=0,top=0'); return false"><img alt="Gelatiamo3" src="http://seattlebonvivant.typepad.com/seattle_bon_vivant/images/Gelatiamo3-thumb.JPG" width="149" height="112" border="0" style="float: left; margin: 0px 5px 5px 0px;" /></a><strong>Maria Coassin</strong> (as Italian as they come, her family are Gelato experts back in Italy) and <strong>Howard Batten</strong>, the owners of Gelatiamo, have imported everything in the shop from Italy. From the ice cream machines to the floor tiles, the espresso makers to the recipes for everything they sell in the shop. Its all Italy, all the time. Ice cream just does not get any better than this. The flavors and textures of their <strong>gelatos</strong> and <strong>sorbettos</strong> have no equal. Rich, creamy and luscious. </p>

<p>My favorites are <strong>Coconut</strong> (no better coconut ice cream in the city), <strong>Rice</strong> (Amazing, with grains of rice cooked in it), <strong>Pistachio</strong>, <strong>Chocolate</strong>. <strong>Passion fruit</strong> and <strong>Mango</strong> too but there are many, many more. We had a lovely time and the ice cream was scrumptious. Sitting outside, people watching, making dinner and weekend plans (Vancouver here we come!), while the air cooled down a bit, time went by without us noticing. </p>

<p>A quick walk to Fourth & Virginia to our new favorite neighborhood spot, <strong>Lola</strong> for an impromptu dinner. No reservations and no worries. After such a wonderful day and delicious gelato, we just knew we were in luck. No need to concern ourselves with finding a table. We would surely find one. Besides, dessert had <em>already</em> been served. </p>

<p></p>

<p></p>

<p><br />
<strong><A href="http://www.gelatiamo.com/">Gelatiamo</A></strong><br />
<strong>1400 3 Rd Avenue<br />
SEATTLE, WA 98101 <br />
Phone: 206.467.9563<br />
Fax: 206.467.9564<br />
E-mail:gelatiamo@msn.com</strong></p>
			</div>
			
			
			
		</div>
		<p class="entry-footer">
			<span class="post-footers">06:00 AM</span> <span class="separator">|</span> <a class="permalink" href="http://seattlebonvivant.typepad.com/seattle_bon_vivant/2004/07/gelatiamo.html">Permalink</a>
							| <a href="http://seattlebonvivant.typepad.com/seattle_bon_vivant/2004/07/gelatiamo.html#comments">Comments (0)</a>
			
			
		</p>
	</div>
			<h2 class="date-header">Friday, July 16, 2004</h2>
	
	<div class="entry" id="entry-1781924">
					<h3 class="entry-header">Eat, Drink & Be Merry: Bite of Seattle</h3>
		
		<div class="entry-content">
			<div class="entry-body">
				<p><a href="http://seattlebonvivant.typepad.com/seattle_bon_vivant/images/seattle_center_will_host_once_again_the_bite_of_seattle_july_1618_20041.html" onclick="window.open('http://seattlebonvivant.typepad.com/seattle_bon_vivant/images/seattle_center_will_host_once_again_the_bite_of_seattle_july_1618_20041.html','popup','width=336,height=386,scrollbars=no,resizable=no,toolbar=no,directories=no,location=no,menubar=no,status=no,left=0,top=0'); return false"><img alt="seattle_center_will_host_once_again_the_bite_of_seattle_july_1618_2004" src="http://seattlebonvivant.typepad.com/seattle_bon_vivant/images/seattle_center_will_host_once_again_the_bite_of_seattle_july_1618_2004-thumb.JPG" width="249" height="287" border="0" style="float: left; margin: 0px 5px 5px 0px;" /></a>Yes, ladies and gents. It is that time of the year when the <strong>Puget Sound</strong> area meets at <strong>Seattle Center</strong> to eat drink and be merry, catch some rays and perhaps cool off at the fountain. Last year's <strong><A href="http://www.biteofseattle.com/home/default.aspx">Bite of Seattle</A></strong was a lot of fun and with this years wonderful weather and vendor lineup, it should be as good or better.</p>

<p>The festival will include a <strong>Vines of Washington </strong> tasting exhibit. It will feature <strong>11 Washington wineries</strong>. (<strong>Snoqualmie Vineyards</strong>, <strong>Hogue Cellars</strong>, <strong>Claar Cellars</strong>, <strong>Samson Estates Winery</strong>, <strong>Maryhill Winery</strong>, <strong>Avery Lane Winery</strong>, <strong>Waterbrook Winery</strong>, <strong>Cave B Estate Winery</strong>, <strong>Balcom & Moe Winery</strong>,  <strong>Terra Blanca</strong> and <strong>Arbor Crest Wine Cellars</strong>)  </p>

<p>A reminder: Our dear <strong>Monorail</strong> has been out of commission since the Memorial Day fire so please visit the <strong>Bite of Seattle</strong> or <strong><A href="http://www.seattlecenter.com/">Seattle Center</A></strong> sites for <strong><A href="http://www.biteofseattle.com/get/">transportation</A></strong> alternatives.</p>
			</div>
			
			
			
		</div>
