			<h2 class="date-header">Wednesday, May 19, 2004</h2>
	
	<div class="entry" id="entry-1435470">
					<h3 class="entry-header">Lunch at Olga's Russian Blinchiki</h3>
		
		<div class="entry-content">
			<div class="entry-body">
				<p>Yesterday afternoon I drove from downtown Seattle to Renton to try out a new Russian restaurant that opened last month, Olga's Blinchiki. The feel is cozy and casual. Comfort food. Russian music playing softly in the background. Russian magazines and periodicals available for diners to browse. Warm and welcoming staff, all Russian natives. Very friendly and helpful. Olga herself is delightful, booming with energy and a beautiful smile, making sure everyone is happy and well fed (Americans and Russians). <BR><BR><img alt="wall" src="http://seattlebonvivant.typepad.com/seattle_bon_vivant/images/wall.JPG" width="252" height="150" border="0"  /><BR><BR>The walls a beautiful shade of yellow, with stencilled birch trees and mischievous kitties (even inside their restroom facilities the birch and cats stencilled wall theme continues)<BR><BR><img alt="lunch" src="http://seattlebonvivant.typepad.com/seattle_bon_vivant/images/lunch.JPG" width="256" height="150" border="0"  /><BR><BR>A delicious lunch of Blinchiki (Russian crepes) , wonderful Borscht (garnished with sour cream and a side of black Russian bread) a pickled carrot, onion and cucumber salad. I ate most of it but was already anticipating dessert: <strong>Jolly Time </strong> ice cream, a concotion that according to <strong><A href="http://www.zwire.com/site/news.cfm?newsid=11353567&BRD=1012&PAG=461&dept_id=141552&rfi=6">Olga Plavidal</A></strong>, the owner of the restaurant, came to her "in a dream". A secret ice cream recipe that as part of the Grand Opening celebration is free with purchase of every combination meal. </p>

<p>I even managed to observe a very nice gentleman making <strong>"Pelmeni"</strong> , Russian ravioli with many types of fillings that they serve piping hot at the restaurant and sell frozen to go.<BR><BR><img alt="pelmeni" src="http://seattlebonvivant.typepad.com/seattle_bon_vivant/images/pelmeni.JPG" width="256" height="192" border="0"  /><BR><BR> After lunch, I shopped, of course, for some Russian items to take home. Beautifully wrapped and colorful candies, A small red Russian Matryoshka doll, <strong>Mozums Auglu Teja</strong> or Latvian fruit tea (pieces of dried strawberry, cherry, apples, black currant, grapes, black ash berry, rosehip, hibiscus and orange peel) and a bottle of <strong>Kimmel Kvass Maizes</strong> that I've yet to try.<BR><BR><img alt="jolly_time" src="http://seattlebonvivant.typepad.com/seattle_bon_vivant/images/jolly_time.JPG" width="256" height="192" border="0"  /><BR><BR> Since I had to drive back to work I took the ice cream with me and ate it by the spoonful along the way. It was scrumptious! A creamy and foamy vanilla based butterscotch, caramel ice cream so unique that I'm already salivating with anticipation for an encore. Jolly Time it was! It took me about 20 minutes to arrive in downtown Seattle. By then, the ice cream had been devoured.</p>

<p>Next time I'm in Renton, I'm making another stop at Olga's. It was <strong>well</strong> worth the drive. </p>

<p><strong>Olga's Russian Blinchiki<br />
95 South Tobin St.<br />
Renton, WA 98055<br />
(425) 917 8799</strong></p>
			</div>
			
			
			
