	<div class="entry" id="entry-1253643">
					<h3 class="entry-header">Attack of the evil 2,4,6-Trichloroanisole...</h3>
		
		<div class="entry-content">
			<div class="entry-body">
				<p>TCA in the house! It was bound to happen sooner or later, no? Monday night. My first corked bottle! EVER! :-( <BR><BR>Had my friend D over for dinner...to catch up on trip, latest news, new boy and to sample my latest experiment with baby back ribs...a variation of my friend Alfie's recipe...sans Dark Ale, with plenty of onions and garlic.  Decided on a bottle of <strong>Domaine de la Petite Cassagne 2000 Cotières de Nîmes</strong> (a Robert Kacher import). A promising blend ( 50% Grenache, 20% Syrah, 25% Carignan and 10% Cinsault) with wonderful reviews that I had been told was an affordbale, everyday alternative to Chateaueneuf-du-Pape. Purchased at Mais Oui! in Bellevue a few months ago. ($10.99)  Well, I could not take a second sip. I just knew it was tainted with TCA the second it hit my mouth. So..my trusty <strong>Chateau Saint-Sulpice Bordeaux 2001 (Appellation Bordeaux Controlée), a blend of Merlot and Cabernet </strong> came to the rescue. A baby green spinach salad with crumbled Maytag, cranberries and candied pecans. Raspberry Vinaigrette. Steamed baby creamers. Ribs. Chocolate and more fun conversation for dessert.  Too bad about the Cassagne. </p>
			</div>
			
			
			
		</div>
		<p class="entry-footer">
			<span class="post-footers">08:44 PM</span> <span class="separator">|</span> <a class="permalink" href="http://seattlebonvivant.typepad.com/seattle_bon_vivant/2004/04/attack_of_the_e.html">Permalink</a>
							| <a href="http://seattlebonvivant.typepad.com/seattle_bon_vivant/2004/04/attack_of_the_e.html#comments">Comments (0)</a>
			
			
		</p>
	</div>


						</div>
					</div>
					<div id="gamma">
						<div id="gamma-inner" class="pkg">
							<!-- sidebar2 -->


